comment: An _incidence structure_ ` <. P , L , I >. ` "where ` P ` is a set whose elements are called _points_, ` L ` is a distinct set whose elements are called _lines_ and ` I C_ ( P X. L ) ` is the _incidence relation_" (see Wikipedia "Incidence structure" (24-Oct-2020), ~ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incidence_structure ) implies an undirected hypergraph, if the incidence relation is right-total (to exclude empty edges). The points become the vertices, and the edge function is derived from the incidence relation by mapping each line ("edge") to the set of vertices incident to the line/edge. With ` P = ( Base `` S ) ` and by defining two new slots for lines and incidence relations (analogous to ` LineG ` and ` Itv ` ) and enhancing the definition of ` iEdg ` accordingly, it would even be possible to express that a corresponding incidence structure _is_ an undirected hypergraph. By choosing the incident relation appropriately, other kinds of undirected graphs (pseudographs, multigraphs, simple graphs, etc.) could be defined. (Contributed by AV, 24-Oct-2020.)
